d. The first word in a sentence is always conspicuous in interest and importance. Very often it is a noun, pro- noun, or phrase referring to the preceding sentence or to some part of it ε

e. The most important word or combination of words is often taken out from a subordinate introductory sentence and placed at the very beginning before the connective introducing that sentence. This order is especially common with cum clauses of time and cause. The word or phrase thus made emphatic is often such as has been described in d above:

Latin us dum ad Tiberim descendit, sacerdos bovem immolavit.

In quem postquam omnium Era conversa sunt, ad finum omnes Scipionem in Hispania proconsulem esne iusserunt.
